    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Test samples' factor as defined in ASME V&V 40-2018 addresses variability arising from biological specimen sampling strategies in device testing (e.g., sample-to-sample variability in animal or human tissue properties used for physical prototype testing). This CFD credibility assessment does not involve physical device prototypes or biological tissue specimens as test articles; the validation evidence is drawn from in-vitro bench experiments using controlled bovine blood at a single hematocrit protocol. Specimen sampling variability is not a source of uncertainty in this assessment — blood fluid properties are treated as input parameters with documented distributions in the model inputs factor. Accordingly, this factor does not apply to the present computational V&V 40 assessment context and is marked not-applicable."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The 'Equivalency of input parameters' factor addresses situations where validation experiments are conducted on a surrogate or scaled geometry that differs from the clinical device, requiring a formal equivalency argument to bridge the gap. In this assessment, validation experiments were conducted directly on the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry under VAD operating conditions that are identical to the COU; no surrogate geometry, scaled model, or predicate device substitution was employed. Because the validation domain and the COU domain share the same geometry and operating envelope, no equivalency bridging argument is required or applicable. This factor is therefore not-applicable to the present assessment."
    }
